The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                 NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, Jan. 27 (PTI): A senior Supreme Court judge today likened terrorists killing innocent people to animals and said they cannot be allowed to take benefit of human rights.          
	Those who violate the rights of society and have no respect for human rights cannot be a human, Justice Arijit Pasayat said at a seminar on terrorism. We should not talk about human rights violation of terrorists because terrorists are the people who kill innocent people with AK-47 and AK-56.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The Supreme Court has issued a notice to the Delhi government on a bail petition of Utsav Bhasin, who had allegedly mowed down a man with his BMW last September. The government has to reply in two weeks.                   
	 Dehra Dun (PTI): Beijing Olympics gold medal winner Abhinav Bindra will set up a five-star hotel in Dehra Dun, the proposal for which was recently cleared by the Uttarakhand government. The project, estimated to cost Rs 150-200 crore, will be undertaken by his fathers company.                   
	 London (PTI): The body of an Indian teenager, missing since early January, has been recovered from a canal in London. The body of 15-year-old Jonathan Marques from Goa has been sent for post-mortem. He had left home to go to school on January 6 but did not return.                  
	 New Delhi (PTI): The Supreme Court has said an apprentice cannot be construed to be an employee even if he is given a stipend as he is a trainee undergoing training in an organisation. National Insurance Company had repudiated a claim of M/s Abhilash Jewellery, Kerala, for the loss of 587.870 grams of gold. The insurance company said the lost articles were in the custody of an apprentice, who were not an employee in the full sense.                  
	 Attari (PTI): About 14kg of heroin was seized from four passengers, two of them women, on the Samjhauta Express on Monday. The heroin, worth Rs 70 crore, was allegedly being smuggled from Pakistan.                                                                                                                            
